title: For Sale:  SKS Type 56, Very Early Ghost Gun, Sino Soviet
postcontent:
This SKS looks like an Albanian trooper carried it through a rain storm and slept with it in a cave while guarding the border with Greece.  When he got bored he carved his initials and doodled some military emblems into the stock.  At one point, he carved a big square into one side of the stock.  We'll never know why, but it is kind of cool.

This SKS looks rough but functions perfectly.  I picked this up a while back for fun, cleaned it up, took apart the bolt and cleaned it inside out (firing pin functions perfectly, no slam fires here).  I've run a bunch of steel case through it and it eats it all no problem.  I don't need to sell it, it's a fun gun to have, but I'm not a collector.  I thought I would like it for hunting hogs but really like my AR better.

This gun has only the serial number and no arsenal or Chinese markings.  From what I understand, these are referred to as ghost guns and are very early guns.  This one, from what I can tell, is from 1956.

Asking $400 or best offer.  Open to trades but would prefer cash.  If interested please respond via email with name and contact information.  I am real and I will get back to you.

Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  action arms galil 223
postcontent:
Here's a very scarce and highly desirable Pre-Ban "Assault Rifle". This is an Israeli made Galil ARM. Manufactured by Iraeli Military Industries (I.M.I.), this weapon is designated a Model 392 and was imported by Action Arms Inc prior to 1989. It is chambered for the .223 Remington and features a 16" barrel with flash hider. The Galil is a modified and improved version of the famous Kalashnikov (AK47) design. It was specifically manufactured to fire the .223 cartridge and to function flawlessly in the arid (and sandy) desert environment of the Middle East. The Galil was selected as the weapon of choice by the Israeli Defense Forces, beating out the M16A1, AK47, and HK33 among others. Other features include a milled receiver, wood handguard, folding carry handle, integral bipod, AK style safety w/ additional left-side thumb safety, and heavy duty side-folding stock. This weapon is in excellent, near new condition. no rust or pitting at all. Looking at the internals, I cannot tell if this rifle has even been fired! the mechanics are in perfect working order and the bore is likewise excellent. The Galil was imported in rather small numbers and only a few hundred of the Model 392 are in the Country. Blue Book on this rifle is $3100-$3450...if you can find one! This is a hard to find and much sought after pre-ban "assault rifle".

Please note that I use the term "assault rifle" loosely and only due to the popularity of the phrase. A real assault rifle is selective-fire with full auto capabilities while this is a semi-automatic rifle, of course.

title: For Sale:  M94 Swedish Cavalry Carbine
location: North Jersey, New Jersey, United States
postcontent:
Testing the waters on my Swedish M94-14. These are pretty uncommon. 

This is a 1903 dated Carl Gustav, all parts matching except the bolt. Bore on the rifle is immaculate, especially for a 112 year old rifle. Also interesting is this rifle's stock disc. All swedish mausers had inlets cut for a stock disc on the right side of the stock, but a few rifles had discs inletted in to the comb of the stock. No one really seems to know why. 

Stock is in decent shape, with plenty of nicks and character marks. No cracks. 

I've only seen one other 94 in person, at Heritage Guild in Easton. They have one for 1300. I'd like to get in the neighborhood of 1100 for this one, also interested in milsurp rifles of similar value. Garands, AG42, even an SVT with cash on my end. Not really in a hurry to sell, just testing the waters.

title: For Sale:  Colt M1991 A1 1911; very little use; original case and mag
postcontent:
Selling to help pay for a family member's needed dental work.  Bought this from the original owner who got it when he left the service back in the early 90's (or so he said; he seemed fairly believable and the condition seems to support his account).  He shot a box through it, then cleaned it and stored it until he sold it to me about a year ago. Essentially a safe queen.  I've shot about two boxes through it.  It is clean, pristine, and ready to go.  Flat black parkerized finish, factory fixed sights, and original Colt grips.  In addition to the original Colt 8 round mag, it also comes with a Kimber stainless 7 round mag, an unmarked stainless 7 round mag, and a ProMag black 8 round mag.  Comes with original brown Colt case, and a set of Pachmayer finger-notched rosewood grips that I paid $45 for (Bass Pro Shops).   It's a fine gun, no problems or issues, and in the 2 boxes I've shot through it I've no misfeeds, jams, stovepipes, or failures to eject.  The 1911 format just isn't for me.  I've shot 9mm for too long I guess.  Prices on Gunbroker are putting these anywhere from $800 to $1000, so with the condition, lack of use, extra mags, and the Pachmayer grips, I'm asking $850. 

Now, if you can't or won't comply with the following, please don't contact me: You will need to meet me at a public place/parking lot, and provide a valid NH driver's license as well as a valid NH permit to carry a concealed weapon, so that I can know you're allowed to own firearms.  If not, we'll have to meet at a local FFL (Riley's, Morse's, etc.) for background check, and I'd be willing to split the cost there (usually $25).
